7. Encryption Key
Definition

An Encryption Key is a secret value used during encryption and decryption.

The key determines how the plaintext is transformed into ciphertext.

Without the correct key, the encrypted data cannot be correctly decrypted.

Real-Life Analogy

Imagine a locker.

The locker represents encrypted data.

The key represents the encryption key.

Without the correct key:

Locker

↓

Cannot Open

With the correct key:

Locker

↓

Opens Successfully
Important Concept

The algorithm can be public.

The key must remain secret.

Security depends on protecting the key, not hiding the algorithm.

This principle is known as Kerckhoffs's Principle.

8. Encryption Algorithms
Definition

An Encryption Algorithm is the mathematical procedure used to convert plaintext into ciphertext.

Think of it as a recipe.

The algorithm tells the computer how to encrypt data.

The key determines which result is produced.

Algorithm vs Key
Encryption Algorithm	Encryption Key
Mathematical method	Secret value
Publicly known	Must remain secret
Defines encryption process	Produces unique ciphertext
Example

Message:

Hello

Algorithm:

AES

Key:

Secret123

↓

Ciphertext:

P8#Kx91L@

Using the same algorithm but a different key produces completely different ciphertext.

9. Types of Encryption (Introduction)

Encryption is divided into two categories.

Symmetric Encryption

Uses:

One secret key

The same key encrypts and decrypts data.

Examples:

AES
DES
ChaCha20
Asymmetric Encryption

Uses:

Public Key
Private Key

Examples:

RSA
ECC

These will be discussed in detail in the next chapter.

Encryption vs Hashing

Many beginners confuse these concepts.

Encryption	Hashing
Reversible	One-way
Uses Keys	Usually No Key
Protects Confidentiality	Protects Integrity
Original Data Can Be Recovered	Original Data Cannot Be Recovered
